<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Second-Order LHCC </title>

	<p>
		After mastering first-order LHCC equations, we are now ready to tackle second-order LHCC equations. These equations are slightly more complex but follow a similar approach. We'll see how the characteristic equation helps us find solutions and explore the different cases that arise based on its roots.
	</p>
	
	<p>
		A second-order LHCC equation has the form:
		<me> 
			a_2 y'' + a_1 y' + a_0 y = 0 \qquad (a_2, a_1, a_0 \text{ constants})
		</me>.
		In this case, the characteristic equation is given by
		<men xml:id="second-order-characteristic-equation"> 
			a_2 r^2 + a_1 r + a_0 = 0 
		</men>,
		which is a quadratic equation with unknown <m>r</m>. Since quadratic equations have two solutions (possibly repeated), then general solution will have two terms. What the terms look like, depends on the solutions to equation <xref ref="second-order-characteristic-equation"/>. To prepare for the next discussion, review <xref ref="solving-the-quadratic-equation" text="title"/>.
	</p>

	<p>
		At this point you might be thinking that since <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are the solutions to the characteristic equation, then the general solution is simply
		<men xml:id="naive-second-order-lhcc-solution"> 
			y = C_1 e^{r_1 x} + C_2 e^{r_2 x} 
		</men>
		and you'd actually be correct most of the time. The problem is the case when <m>r_1 = r_2</m>, since the terms would combine in <xref ref="naive-second-order-lhcc-solution"/> giving you one term
		<me> y = C_1 e^{r_1 x} + C_2 e^{r_1 x} = (\us{C}{\ub{C_1 + C_2}}) e^{r_1 x} </me>
		but the solution must have two non-like terms (i.e. terms that cannot be combined with addition).
	</p>

	<p>
		Let <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> be the two solutions to equation <xref ref="second-order-characteristic-equation"/> and <m>\Delta = b^2 - 4ac\ </m> be the discriminant of our characteristic equation <xref ref="second-order-characteristic-equation"/>. The value of <m>\Delta</m> will be your guide to what your general solution looks like. In particular, 
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					If <m>\Delta \ne 0</m>, then both <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are different and the general solution is
					<me> y = C_1 e^{r_1 x} + C_2 e^{r_2 x} </me>
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>

		<me> a r^2 + b r + c = 0 </me>.
		<ul>
			<li>
				<p>
					suppose <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> be the two solutions and 
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					Equation <xref ref="second-order-characteristic-equation"/> can be factored as
					<md>
						<mrow> (r - r_1)(r - r_2) = 0 </mrow>
					</md>.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					<m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are either real or complex numbers.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					If <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are real, then they could be different or repeated. <xref ref="quadratic-equation-fact-1" text="custom">Fact 1</xref>
				</p>
			</li>


		</ul>
	</p>
	
	<p>
		The solutions to this quadratic characteristic equation, <m>a_2 r^2 + a_1 r + a_0 = 0</m>, determine the form of the general solution to our second-order LHCC equation. There are three distinct cases based on the discriminant <m>\Delta = a_1^2 - 4a_2a_0</m>:
	</p>
	
	<assemblage><title> Summary of Cases </title>
		<p>
			Depending on the value of the discriminant <m>\Delta</m>, the roots of the characteristic equation and the corresponding general solutions can be summarized as follows:
			<dl width="narrow">
				<li><title>Case 1: Distinct Real Roots (<m>\Delta &gt; 0</m>)</title>
				<p>
					If <m>\Delta &gt; 0</m>, the characteristic equation has two distinct real roots <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m>. The general solution is:
					<me> y = C_1 e^{r_1 x} + C_2 e^{r_2 x} </me>
				</p>
				</li>
				<li><title>Case 2: Repeated Real Roots (<m>\Delta = 0</m>)</title>
				<p>
					If <m>\Delta = 0</m>, the characteristic equation has one repeated real root <m>r</m>. The general solution is:
					<me> y = (C_1 + C_2 x) e^{r x} </me>
				</p>
				</li>
				<li><title>Case 3: Complex Roots (<m>\Delta &lt; 0</m>)</title>
				<p>
					If <m>\Delta &lt; 0</m>, the characteristic equation has two complex conjugate roots <m>r = \alpha \pm \beta i</m>. The general solution is:
					<me> y = e^{\alpha x} (C_1 \cos(\beta x) + C_2 \sin(\beta x)) </me>
				</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</p>
	</assemblage>
	
	<example>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Let's solve the second-order LHCC equation:
			</p>
			<me> y'' - 5y' + 6y = 0 </me>.
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				First, write down the characteristic equation:
			</p>
			<md>
				<mrow> r^2 - 5r + 6 = 0 </mrow>
			</md>.
			<p>
				Solving for <m>r</m> gives two distinct real roots:
			</p>
			<md>
				<mrow> r = 2 \quad \text{and} \quad r = 3 </mrow>
			</md>.
			<p>
				Therefore, the general solution is:
			</p>
			<me> y = C_1 e^{2x} + C_2 e^{3x} </me>.
		</solution>
	</example>
	
	<example>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Consider another example:
			</p>
			<me> y'' + 4y' + 4y = 0 </me>.
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				The characteristic equation is:
			</p>
			<md>
				<mrow> r^2 + 4r + 4 = 0 </mrow>
			</md>.
			<p>
				Solving for <m>r</m> gives a repeated real root:
			</p>
			<md>
				<mrow> r = -2 \quad \text{(double root)} </mrow>
			</md>.
			<p>
				Thus, the general solution is:
			</p>
			<me> y = (C_1 + C_2 x) e^{-2x} </me>.
		</solution>
	</example>
	
	<example>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Finally, let's look at an example with complex roots:
			</p>
			<me> y'' + 2y' + 5y = 0 </me>.
		</statement>
		<solution>
			<p>
				The characteristic equation is:
			</p>
			<md>
				<mrow> r^2 + 2r + 5 = 0 </mrow>
			</md>.
			<p>
				Solving for <m>r</m> gives complex roots:
			</p>
			<md>
				<mrow> r = -1 \pm 2i </mrow>
			</md>.
			<p>
				Therefore, the general solution is:
			</p>
			<me> y = e^{-x} (C_1 \cos(2x) + C_2 \sin(2x)) </me>.
		</solution>
	</example>
	
	<p>
		By recognizing the type of roots the characteristic equation has, we can determine the form of the general solution to any second-order LHCC equation. This method is powerful and provides a systematic approach to solving these equations.
	</p>

	<p>
		<lemma xml:id="concept-lhcc-strategy-cases"><title>Order 2 LHCC General Solution Cases</title><p/>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The 2nd order LHCC DE
					<men xml:id="lhcc-cases-de">
						a\ y'' + b\ y' + c\ y = 0,
					</men>
					with characteristic equation 
					<men xml:id="lhcc-cases-ce">
						a\ r^2 + b\ r + c = 0,
					</men>
					has one the following three general solutions:
					<dl width="narrow">
						<li xml:id="lhcc-case-1"><title> Case 1: if <m>r = r_1, r_2 \,\,</m> are real and different, then </title>
							<p>
								<me> y(x) = c_1\ e^{r_1 x} + c_2\ e^{r_2 x} </me>
							</p>
						</li>
						<li xml:id="lhcc-case-2"><title> Case 2: if <m>r = r_1, r_2 \,\,</m> are real and equal, then </title>
							<p>
								<me> y(x) = c_1\ e^{r_1 x} + c_2\ x\ e^{r_2 x} </me>
							</p>
						</li>
						<li xml:id="lhcc-case-3"><title> Case 3: if <m>r = \alpha \pm i \beta \,\,</m> is complex, then </title>
							<p>
								<me> y(x) = e^{\alpha\ x} (c_1\ \sin(\beta x) + c_2\ \cos(\beta x)) </me>
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</lemma> 
	</p>

	<p>
		Degree 2 characteristic equations have the familiar form
		<me>
			a\ r^2 + b\ r + c = 0,
		</me>
		and have two solutions, found by either factoring, 
		<md>
			<mrow>(r - r_1)(r - r_2) = 0,</mrow>
			<mrow>r = r_1,\ r_2 </mrow>
		</md>
		or, by applying the quadratic formula.
		<fn> 
			The solution to the equation 
			<me> 
				a\ x^2 + b\ x + c = 0, 
			</me> 
			is given by
			<me>
				\text{quadratic formula:} \quad x = \frac{b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}.
			</me>
		</fn>
		Since the values you get from either method are the same, we can technically write the factoring technique as
		<me>
			(r - r_1)(r - r_2) = 0,
		</me>
		where
		<me>
			r_1 = \frac{b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \quad \text{ and } \quad r_2 = \frac{b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}.
		</me>
	</p>

